This was our first meal after getting the rental car.  It wasn't as good as I was expecting for yelp to have so many 5 star reviews.  The fried spam musubi was solid, but nothing I had to have.

We also had the loco moco, which is like a big bowl of everything.  I must say the serving size was HUGE, but none of it was that good, it felt like just a bunch of stuff thrown together.  A lot of the items were a bit on the salty side too.

It was just my wife and I so I think we ordered way too much.  If you have a group of 4 the items can be split up better.

It was nice that there was a private parking lot.

text:
At Da Kitchen, is about quality is numbah 1. But even more than that, it's about quantity. This original Da Kitchen, located in the same spot at Kahului's Triangle Square (what a dumb name, but I digress), has been a source of upscale local food. Despite the growing and changing a bit, the place still has it!

Now, you gotta know that the atmosphere is usually a bit hectic and the interior is always LOUD. Also, Da Kitchen has a little bit of an attitude engrained at the institutional level. It's like Da Kitchen is awesome (and always has been) and they know it. It's not that the people aren't friendly nor do the servers neglect you. But the servers, running circuits around the dining room, are almost too busy. This attitude manifested in a super defensive explanation of the restaurant's practice of not providing water unless requested that was typed up and displayed under the plexi tabletop. While the water policy is no longer displayed, I now have major guilt about ever having water at a restaurant. (Do you know it costs big bugs to wash da cup you wen use?)

The location recently underwent a bit of a renovation and there are some tradeoffs. First, the sassy note  The dining room now fits a lot more people. When I went last, there was no line (granted, I was there a little after the lunch rush). It was probably a better place for groups before they removed the oversized booths (seriously, they would seat like 8 people). But it's still okay for small-to-medium size groups. Just know that you're gonna have to wait for adjacent parties to leave so that tables can be put together.

Sure, the prices have spiked, but you'll for sure have enough for leftovers! And it's definitely a prime first and last stop on the way from or to the airport (and you'll want those leftovers for any long flight!).

text:
What a beautiful state park. This one is very accessible with a road that drives along the entire length of the canyon.

There are so many stops along the side of the road with great viewpoints. The canyon is breath taking.

Some of the stops have hiking, but with only a day here, we didn't have time to explore any of them.

The very end of the road is supposed to have a great view point of the Napali Coast, but when we got there it was completely covered in fog.

This is a must see in Kauai for sure!
business_description: Expansive, mountain top gorge known as the "Grand Canyon of the Pacific" features sweeping views.

text: I did the canyon trail to waterfall.  Two waterfalls at the end. As you approach  the end do not go down the cliff side you can fall. Stay on the left. Eventually, you can either turn left or right. Both sides have a view of waterfalls.(not big but beautiful). One you can jump into and the other is only for viewing. Come early around 7-8. It gets really crowded. If you go when its raining  bring hiking shoes and walking  stick. During a sunny day sneakers are good. I saw kids and elderly doing the trail in sandals! I honestly  would not bring sandals. Bring lots of water. Hike down is easier than up. If you want to extend it go down the black pipe trail too. You will be in for a great hike. I would not bring kids if its raining.

text: The best thing about this place was that it was uncrowded and free. If you have been to Hawaii that is something you can't normally say. Even the drive there is interesting with multiple pullouts, many in rough, unimproved condition. Don't pass them by, as there are great vistas worth seeing. There are a few side roads on your way up. I recommend you take one or two of them on your way back down from the main attraction. They are less crowded and offer closer and better views of the waterfall. All the roads down the mountain lead to the same little town so explore without worrying. I feel so sorry for those who drive all the way up, then all the way down without stopping at all the walkable sites and photo opportunities.

text:
This is amazingly beautiful.  I have NOT been to the Grand Canyon, yet, but I understand why this is called the Grand Canyon of the Pacific.  It is accessible by car but longer than a 30 minute drive into the mountains.  There are also hiking trails, some of which should only be attempted by EXPERIENCED hikers.  If you are not comfortable driving, there are tours that will take you to see this incredible creation of God.

There are restrooms, water and vendors if you need a snack.  DO NOT GO without a camera or you will regret it.
business_description: Expansive, mountain top gorge known as the "Grand Canyon of the Pacific" features sweeping views.

text: I set out early from Lihue at around 6am and I'm glad I did as there barely was any traffic on the road. It's easy to miss the first road going up but I'm glad I did because I took the second road and it was a beautiful drive up, although at some point, I did wonder as didn't meet anyone on that road, if whether or not I'm gonna run a deer over anytime soon. Dress for cool weather. Another reason to drive up early, you'll have the entire lookout for yourself, and truly great if you brought your photography gears with you. There are several lookouts, and you'll be tempted to stop at every single one of them. The road eventually ends at the Kalalau valley lookout. Yet another reason to be there early is because of visibility, try to avoid afternoon drives because the clouds descend by that time. You'll see nothing but clouds at the Niihau island lookout area. There are plenty of short trails you can take as well. Waimea is stupendously pretty. The canyon is completely different because of the vegetation, yet has similarity with the GC.

So much going on in this park that there is something here for everyone. Beautiful views from the overlooks. Great hiking into the canyon. You have to drive through the park to get to the Kokee Park overlooks and trails for the top of the Napali Coast. You can't go wrong with spending valuable vacation time in this park.

Only unfortunate item in my experience is some peoples inability to drive narrow mountain roads or they over estimate their ability to drive four wheel drive vehicles on rough roads so know your abilities and treat other drivers appropriately. text: It's hard to understand how so many people come to Kauai and never check out this beautiful island canyonland. It has been compared to the Grand Canyon in Arizona and with reason. It is not as large and deep, but it is stunningly beautiful. The rust red soil contrasts the green vegetation and has amazing cuts from the natural erosion over years of rainwater runoff. This State park has great signs explaining the history and evolution of the area along with how the first inhabitants of the island used the vegetation to live and grow into a civilization. It is amazing that they do not charge an entrance fee. This is definately a must see area and a fantastic hiking location.  Make sure you have a hat and plenty of water. Some of the trails are strenuous so go to Koke'e State park for a map. Plus, this is a hunting area and people use dogs to hunt wild pigs so don't interfere with the hunter and dogs.

text:
Waimea Canyon and Kokee State Parks are two of KAUAI'S natural gems. Situated on the west side of the island 17 miles and roughly 4000 ft above Waimea Town, this state park some of the most breathtaking views and inspiring hikes. At almost every mile marker there is a possibility of an epic photo. Check out my photo for a listing of all hikes in both state parks.

Remember to enjoy responsibly. Do not pass any sections that are marked as off limits, do not hike out of your comfort zone, and ensure someone is with you or knows where you are. These hikes are not necessarily long but the elevation gain and loss adds alrererendnloss level of intensity that changes their dynamic. Bring plenty of water and the proper footwear.

Lastly, respect the Aina. The only way a natural wonder stays this pristine  is through care and love. Pack out what you pack in, cleanup after yourself, stay on the trail, and stay safe.

Mahalo and Namaste,
mpgink

text:
The beginning part of the journey up Waimea Canyon Drive is incredibly deceptive. It is dry and barren and quite unimpressive apart from the view back towards Waimea.
Keep driving and your perseverance will be rewarded. The first stunning sight that is revealed is a series of waterfalls tumbling over a red dirt hill.
A short drive leads to a turn for the car park for the Waimea Canyon lookout.
I recommend that you save the lookout for your return trip.
Instead, keep driving to the Kalalau Valley Lookout and, at the very end of the road, the Pu'u O Kila Lookout. The views are absolutely breathtaking and best seen early before the clouds roll in.
On the way back, you can stop at the Waimea Canyon Lookout which is largely unaffected by the weather, unlike the Kalalau Valley Lookout and the Pu'u O Kila Lookout.
Highly recommend Waimea Canyon Park!

text: This is a beautiful state park....IF you get to see it. :-) we saw it from the air on a wonderful helicopter tour, but the next day we wanted to go see it in person, too. We drove up around 9 am and caught a glimpse of the canyon from the first lookout point. But, as we wound up the canyon round to the final lookout point, it was completely covered in fog. It was raining, too. So... If you catch the canyon on a rainy day (which will happen since Kauai is home to the wettest spot on earth!) you've just got to be willing to wait out the weather to see it in all its glory.

text: This park is stunning. As you drive up Waimea Canyon drive, there are tons of photo spots and places to pull over. You will have 8 million photos, because everything is so pretty. Try and bring a camera that is either not a phone camera or if it is a phone, take some panorama shots- we found those to be the best at actually capturing what we were seeing. If it is cloudy, wait a minute! Sometimes the clouds move so fast that it clears up in a minute or two, you just have to be patient. We went all the way to the end of the road, and tried to to the Pihea trail hike that preceeds the swamp trail. We went quite a ways but it started raining, so we went back. It's not a hike I would recommend in the rain, especially for beginners as it can get very slippery with all the clay mud. Heads up for Hawaii State parks tourists- bring hand sanitizer for the washroom, or your own soap. They never have soap in the washroom and when we went, the water didn't work in one of the washrooms either.

text:
This is the most beautiful place I've ever seen. Absolutely stunning.

I laughed when I saw other people downgraded it because their rental car overheated on the trek from sea level to more than 4,500 feet in elevation by the end of the road at the 19-mile mark or they went on a day when the canyon was clouded in.

The Canyon Trail accessed from the Pu'u Hinahina Lookout jut past the 13-mile marker comes out on a ridge near Waipo'o Falls. There are breathtaking views there. Just don't venture too far along the edge. It's a 700-foot fall.

The most magnificent view are from the Pu'u o Kila Lookout at the end of the road. It looks into the Kalalau Valley on the Na Pali Coast. An unforgettable sight.

Waimea Canyon Road is the more scenic of the two roads that access the canyon. Koke'e Road, farther west in Kekaha, also climbs the canyon and joins Waimea Canyon Road seven miles up, but it's not as scenic.

text:
Relocated at Aloha Tower Marketplace, the current version of The Old Spaghetti Factory is cleaner, brighter, and a better experience than the former location.  The staff was attentive on my last two visits, and food came out within an acceptable time frame, well plated and tasting as it should.

The salads came out heavily dressed, so ask for your dressing on the side if that isn't your thing.

While no reservations are required, they are highly recommended for lunch, or if you want to sit in the faux streetcar set in the middle of the restaurant.

text: Went for a birthday lunch the other day.  First visit at the new location.  Was pleased to see the time honored decor in place which leads to the charm and overall ambiance that one remembers from the old spagetthi factory at Ward Warehouse.  The restaurant was clean, bathrooms clean.  We were seated promptly and even got to choose where we sat.  Our server was friendly and available whenever we needed anything.   The food was as good as remembered and I learned something new, you can substitute Angel hair pasta for regular spaghetti which is really great with the mushroom sauce and mizithra cheese combbo plate.  The broccoli is awesome.  Decent wine selections which are not through the roof expensive...  lovely place to have a casual meal and revelry with good friends or family.  Bar seating also available if you have to dine alone and are not comfortable sitting alone on a table.

There is a large selection of donuts, but the snow puffs and the buttered roll was the family favorites.  Almost had to go back for more.  There is easy parking and the staff is very helpful and patient even though it was packed at the time.  It is worth the drive to North shore for this and the sights.

text:
I probably drive around the island once or twice a month and I end up around the North Shore towards the end of the day and if it's around 6PM I always hit this place up.

Why? Because from 6 to 7 PM daily all their fresh baked goods in their display cases are HALF OFF!. It does not apply to the stuff on their shelves like cookies, sanwhiches, loaf bread.

Personally I like their snow puffies, turn overs and old fashioned doughnuts. Snow puffies are best eaten the same day but will hold up reasonably well to the next morning.

text: First time here. Always have seen pictures of their snow puffies but never tried them. Took the chance after seeing the sunflower field close by. When we parked it was clear it was good because there was a line. Small bakery basically it was kind of a pickup window where you could see what they had but not enough room to linger everyone in line managed to squeeze into the shop but told they had ran out of snow puffies and it would take 30 minutes. I don't think it was normal for them to run out of snow puffies but we waited along with maybe thirty other people it was very hot but you could buy cups of Jell-O and some drinks from the refrigerator or water from the store next door. The snow puffies took a while for them to make but they were worth it and delicious.

Our table was right in the walkway (no problem with the location of it) and my hair was blowing everywhere from the door being open and it was freezing. Guests at other tables not even directly hit by it were complaining amongst one another. We asked the waiter if they could close that and while we didn't see him as the manager, he told us she had said no. Finally we asked if we could move because it was becoming ridiculous, which we were able to.

text:
The experience at Pulehu is of an almost elegant restaurant.   It is open to the Ka'anapali beach air.  The lighting is wonderful.  The space is generous.  The glassware is fine.  But where are the tablecloths?

So the ambiance is -- almost -- first rate.  The service IS top notch.

But the food is just on the high side of so-so.   And that, after all, is why you go to a restaurant, isn't it?

So overall, Pulehu is better than its food.

The prices though, are what you'd expect from a high-end hotel restaurant, so the value just isn't there.

As for that recommendation for the canonical friend, I seldom choose hotel restaurants, and I only recommend them when they are truly outstanding.
business_description: Classic Italian dishes with an island twist served in a rustic-chic, open-air space at the Westin.

text:
This is a beautiful scenic restaurant located in the Westin North Villas at Kaanapali. Their food is excellent, and well portioned. All local grown produce or local farmed fish used in the entrees.  Freshly made pasta from scratch.

The executive chef provided a food demonstration one afternoon that we attended. Very informative and also gave us some Pulehu bucks at the end of the demonstration that we used on another evening that we dined there.

Their 3 course daily menu offering is very well priced and has a nice variety to choose from. Also can order off the main menu,  or their daily specials.  Wide variety of wine, beer, cocktails and champagne to choose from.

text: Awesome setting, delicious food. Did both the Outdoor Grill and the prix fixe menu in the main restaurant on our trip. Both offer great views, well-prepared food, and refreshing drinks. The wine pairing for the prix fixe was also amazing!

text: This is a go-to favorite for locals and tourists alike. We also all appreciated Merrimans staying open through the pandemic, taking safety seriously, and being so transparent in their communications on social media. The entire team supported our local community through this trying year and were absolutely wonderful. We're fans for life.

text:
It was a cold, windy, rainy night so we had to wait for space indoors even with a reservation, TOTALLY WORTH THE WAIT. Ladies, bring a shall, men a jacket.
The mixed drinks were phenomenal! Lots of veggie options on the starter options, all were delicious although the risotto was 86d by our dinner service. For mains we had the ribeye with polenta, and the shrimp and scallops- both were incredible. The food was so good but easily double the amount I could eat. Favorite dessert were there pineapple bread pudding and the chocolate purse. Incredible service, delicious food.

text:
We made reservations here from a referral of a close friend. Sunset window table was the request for our anniversary celebration. Well that did not work. We got a table in the back of the restaurant. The entire staff was amazing, the food was equally so.
Thank you for going so above and beyond to ensure our special night was one to be remembered for along time to come.
Steve and Kelli

text: Spectacular venue. Great staff. As a industry person, I really appreciated not only the knowledge of our server, but the honesty when we asked a question they did not know. But they came back with the answer. Very professional. We had the opportunity to talk with Tom Bean. We will go back, if for any reason other than to see him again. A remarkable manager; pouring wine, assisting staff, even politely cutting a conversation short to continue ensuring service on the floor...we'd give anything to have him as our manager. Stunning place, as you'd expect from Chef Merriman.

text: Beautiful location, incredible view, open air, immaculate. Service was impeccable; maintaining an upscale yet relaxed beach feel. Quiet enough to hear each other and the waves, yet busy enough to laugh out loud. Orders were presented quicky and with excellent presentation. All the things you'd expect, nailed it. Can't wait to return. I heavily recommend "The Cure", regardless of your adventures the evening prior.

text: I came here on my honeymoon. Every dish was wonderfully complex and delicious. We had a great time and the atmosphere and service was fantastic.

text: Been to Merriman's a dozen times over the years. Have always been impressed but today takes the cake. Reduced COVID restricted tables, 45 min socially distanced line, specials sold out in the first 2 hours of service, no inside seating, only burgers, fish tacos and truffle fries on the menu . . .   It was amazing and we had do much fun. First of all . . . Mai Tai Mondays are for real. Lilikoi foam mai tai with mac nut orgeat!! Bomb cocktail for real! Burger was legit one of the best burgers I've ever had. Fish tacos were fresh and perfect. Truffle fries were cooked perfectly, crispy on the outside, fluffy on the inside and perfectly seasoned. I LOVE THESE GUYS! They figure out a way to make it work during the most challenging times. Great job from top to bottom. Shoots!
business_description: Renowned oceanfront restaurant features farm-to-table cuisine in an elegant setting with views.

text: Best place to watch the sunset with a cocktail in hand. Sit by the fire pit if you can grab a spot early. Very romantic. Great ambiance. Fresh, local Pacific Rim cuisine. Incredible. Owned by famous Pacific Rim Chef Peter Merriman.

text: Super fancy restaurant. If you drive up to the front they only have valet parking, so if you want to park yourself there is a free parking lot right next to the restaurant, and it's about a 3 minute walk. This place definitely has a high class feel, so don't show up in your board shorts and a t shirt. Food is really good, as well as their cocktails. They have a HUGE wine selection, as well as really friendly wait staff. I highly recommend this if you're looking for a romantic dinner, or celebrating anything.  As you may have already guessed, it's not cheap.

text:
We had dinner there last night and were celebrating our Honeymoon.  We called to ask for a great seat since we were celebrating.  To our surprise, we were seated at what was quite possibly one of the best views we have ever seen!  A beautiful sunset, a scenic Bay, and humpback whales.  Simply amazing!  Our server, Solomon, was top notch! I had the filet which was cooked perfectly and she had the fish special.

Afterwards we shared an after dinner drink on the patio under the stars!

Thank you Merrimans for creating a special memory for us!

text: I was honestly more impressed with my room service steak than the steak I had here. After we were seated we received some strange carrot juice cocktail, which seemed oddly out of place and garnered no explanation from our waiter who seemed annoyed to be there. My sister and I both ordered the filet, cooked medium. Hers was cooked perfectly, but my cut of meat was thicker and cooked for the same amount of time, leaving it rare in the middle. The potatoes were cold and unappetizing. My mother ordered the macadamia crusted monchong, which she loved but is no longer on the menu. I hope the tip we left our waiter buys him a new personality, he totally killed the dining experience from the start.

text:

The movie was excellent and taught me a few things I didn't know. The Arizona memorial was closed for construction but the harbor tour put the story in perspective. The memorial garden had interesting pieces of Navy and Japanese equipment.

I would advise getting the headset before the movie and boat tour because you will be dropped off right at the memorial walk which is where most of the information is located.

text:
If you want to experience what it was like Pearl Harbor in 1941 you need to visit the memorial site. They will have movies photos another memorabilia displayed. The Educated Park Rangers will help guide you through the tour. Or you can opt out and do the audio self-guided tour.

There are several Memorial sites at this one Visitor Center. You have the USS Arizona USS bowfin USS Missouri.

There are plenty of indoor activities. Their snack shops and souvenirs.

We did the USS Arizona Memorial who wants to about a 30-minute film and took a 30-minute boat ride out over the boat. We were able to see the remains of the Arizona and drive past the Missouri with plenty of photo opportunities at both sites.

The history in the sacredness of this spot and locations is well conveyed and felt.

This is a great Memorial site to bring young and old they will enjoy it.

The tenacity of these men and the area during those long days and years to follow is shown in this Memorial site.

I'm honored I had the opportunity to come and visit and share my brief experience.  You will enjoy your visit.

text: The Pearl Harbor historic site is informative and emotional. The film is amazing, with real life footage of the attack. But for me it was ultimately disappointing because the Arizona Memorial itself is closed, and that is what I wanted to see on this once in a lifetime trip. Has been closed for over 11 months it turns out because the floating dock leading to the Memorial is unsafe and requires repair. They say it is supposed to reopen March 2019. The Navy and the Park Service do what they can, and very admirably, with the film, markers, and taking you out by boat to near the Arizona. You must stay seated in the boat though, so you can't see the sunken Arizona below the surface. Had I known the actual Memorial was inaccessible, I would have scheduled my trip for after it reopens.

text: It was a great privilege to be able to visit this memorial. We were also able to view it from the air when we done a helicopter tour of the island. Security is tight for entering so leave all bags or you will need to take them off and leave them before entering. So much information about the attack on pearl harbour and walking through the USS Bowfin submarine let you see just how cramped the living conditions were. We weren't able to board the USS Arizona Memorial due to repairs to the boarding ramp but got close enough to see it. Had a hotdog from the restaurant and it was really good. Filled a hole until the evening meal. I think we would have loved to spend more time there but being part of a couch tour we were pressed for time. I would say it is a "must" place to visit if you are in Hawaii.

text: When you arrive make sure you don't have any bags bigger than about 6 inches squared otherwise you will need to check it into their bag check or put it into your car. This includes diaper bags. text:
Yes, these four sites are a tourist attraction, and very popular, but they are also pieces of history that you can see, touch and hopefully learn from. The attack that took place here in December 1941 changed the world forever.

Take the time to visit all four sites (Arizona, Bowfin, Missouri and the Pacific Aviation Museum) and maybe follow that with a trip to Punchbowl. It might take a full day but it is well worth the effort.

Some complain that it is too expensive. I don't think prices are unreasonable at all - especially since the upgrades a few years ago. And what price do you put on education?

Photos are from various visits

text:
This is a must-see when in Honolulu.  I knew the basics about Pearl Harbor, but was too young to really understand a lot of it.  When you come here, it changes you and really moves you.  The tour begins with a video explaining how everything happened.  When you get to the memorial, it's hard not to picture yourself as one of the sailors that was there that dreadful day.

The memorial is beautiful.  Seeing all of the remnants of the ships is incredible.  They're massive.  It's hard not to picture what it used to look like before that day.  Someone at the memorial had said to remember that "the ships below are not only sunken ships....they're a graveyard."  He was right.  They couldn't recover all of the bodies, so some of their bodies are still underneath the memorial.

The wall showing all of the names of people lost was moving.  It brought me to tears.  Seeing each of those names, you want to read them all and think of who they were as people.  It's absolutely breathtaking and worth every moment you get to spend there.

We also did the submarine tour which was awesome.  Very, very tight quarters, but amazing.  You don't get that opportunity too often.  It was amazing to see all the details and what they put into such tiny little spaces to make it seem relatively big.

This can't go unvisited!

text: Dec 7, 1941 was the day the United States entered World War II, and the day over 3,000 lives were lost in the Japanese attack on Oahu.  Pearl Harbor is the generic name that is used to describe the larger attack on Oahu because so many lives were lost on the ships that were in port at Pearl Harbor.  From the Visitor center, a Navy boat takes visitors out onto the Harbor to the newly renovated Arizona Memorial located on top of the sunken hull of the USS Arizona where the remains of over 900 sailors are entombed.  A retired battleship, the USS Missouri, is anchored nearby, and a WWII era submarine, USS Bowfin, is not far away.

text:
Because we were jet-lagged, we woke up super early and decided to check out Pearl Harbor. Here's a tip! RENT A CAR. I'm looking at all these tours and they charge so much money. GUESS WHAT? Pearl Harbor is FREE!! That's right - FREE!!! So don't get ripped off. On the website, it says that they give away 1300 free tickets daily.

Address:
1 Arizona Memorial Road
Honolulu, HI. 96818

Type that address in and you'll arrive at the parking lot.
They do not allow backpacks, purses, fanny packs, camera bags, luggage, diaper bags or shopping bags. Leave it in your car. OR check it in at their lockers - they charge extra but I'm not sure how much.

Once you enter, grab a ticket. You will watch a 25 minute documentary (really interesting) and then you will take a free boat ride to the USS Arizona Memorial (also free) and then you come back and then you can take a walk around.

This place is open from 7:00am - 5:00 pm. First tour starts at 7:45 am and last tour is at 3:00 pm)

It's a beautiful place to visit so spread the word and don't pay money to expensive tour companies.

text:
A very sobering and well done place of remembrance of the men and women who died in or around the Pearl Harbor attack. Everyone associated with the running of the facilities seemed to be very nice and attentive. We had to wait 2 hours to get on the ride to go over to the Arizona Memorial.

Since we had a wait we did the Submarine called the USS Bowfin. What an amazing journey this sub took in WW2. Take the tour!! It's WELL worth it. You will see, feel, smell and hear the sounds of what the brave soldiers went through while riding underneath the water and sinking 44 ships.

There are plenty of food and drink vendors there to keep you happy and refreshed. Lots of nice shopping stores there to buy memorabilia too.

There are a number of walk-thru type tours you can go around and see and hear presentations of what happened during the attack. One tour is all about the USS Bowfin. One of the attack itself. Other displays showing an actual Japanese secret torpedo from the era. Lots of cool flags, badges, letters, artifacts and even periscopes, big guns and missiles you can view into or take pics with.

Once on the ride over to the Arizona, it was a very sobering but yet a very thankful and grateful feeling came over us.

Overall, this is a wonderful voyage back in time. It's amazing that some of those items made it through and are still here today to enjoy and learn about. Great for the whole family. A must see while on the island.

text:
It has been 24 years since I was last here and a lot has changed. I wanted to see the USS Arizona memorial again, but was focused on the whole site as many other lives were lost here and not just those from the USS Arizona.  It is an important piece of our history and I wish others could experience this location once in their life. Luckily, I was also able to see the USS Missouri, the ship my brother served on, decommissioned, and brought here.
One of the more important features is the multitude of information placards about the troops and vessels. I really enjoyed reading about the submarines and their adventures.

text: Your visit to Pearl Harbor Historic Sites begins here. Arrive early to avoid the long lines. I arrived at 6:30 a.m. and the site ticket office opens at 7 a.m. Admission to the USS Arizona Memorial is free, but tickets are issued at a first come first served basis, as a boat trip to the site is required. Prior to the boat trip, a 20 minute video presentation is included and a prerequisite to reach the boat at its conclusion. The visit to the USS Arizona is a solemn occasion. The memorial structure straddles the sunken ship which can still be seen through the clear water and entombed within it are 1177 souls. The Wall of Honor listing the dead is a very moving experience. From the ticket office, you can purchase tickets to the USS Missouri and the Bowfin Submarine as well as the Pacific Aviation Air Museum. At the Pearl Harbor Historic Sites pavilion there's a gift shop and a convenience store as well as a large restrooms. For me, visiting Pearl Harbor Historic sites was the highlight of my visit to Honolulu.

text: Going to Pearl Harbor Visitor Center and taking the boat ride to see the USS Arizona Memorial in the middle of Pear Harbor are some of the "must sees" while in Honolulu. Try to go first thing in the morning during the week. Tickets to see the Memorial are free, but you have to go early because they go quick and the parking lot fills up quickly. I highly recommend you visit the Visitor Center and walk through to see the exhibits. There is an audio tour to purchase that is well worth it. Before taking the 10 min boat ride to the Memorial, be sure to watch the 25 min the informative documentary in the auditorium. You can easily be here for half a day to see everything.

text:
Yes The Attack on Pearl Harbor was a tragedy.  More than 4,000 service men died, but Elvis Presley paid for a major portion of the memorial.  There is a gift shop, free parking and a tremendous amount of placards depicting the entire event.
Get there early as the first 100 people get a free ticket to see the 15 minute movie of the attact and then a boat ride to the actual memorial.  Somber and surreal!!
Captain Stan Howard

text:
If you ever have the opportunity... Do NOT miss going to Pearl Harbor and take the tour.
Yes, Hawaii is beautiful, the weather is great, but one thing you'll never forget is the Pearl Harbor tour. I'd see the movie on tv, I'd hear people talk about the war.... but, until I went to Hawaii the first time in 2004 and my 3rd time in 2018 I can't explain what it is, but it affected me different than the movies and listening to people I know talk about the war, all 3 times I visited.
It's a must see on your vacation.

text: I love everything about these memorials. The Arizona memorial is free of charge, but you have to make sure you get tickets. During the summer months they can be hard to come by as they are on a first come, first serve basis. They escort you in to a room first where you watch a 15 minute video about the attack on Pearl Harbor. Then they lead you out to a boat that takes you to the memorial. You are then granted about 20 minutes to walk around the memorial and pay your respects. Then they take you back. The museum that accompanies the Arizona is a wonderful way to understand the beginning and middle of the war and how it affected the island of Oahu. The Bowfin is a good tour, full of lots of information. I would suggest getting the audio tour because the cramped space of the submarine it's nearly impossible to traverse it "with" someone. Works out a lot better if you have your own audio tour and they have theirs, then you can share your experiences after. The main site is totally free to walk around and read the many information boards. It's also a very good time for reflection, try and be respectful of those that are there to pay their respects. The main site is also free to just walk around you just have to.make sure your not bringing in any bags...purses, diper bags, are all excluded. You'll have to check them outside.

business_description: This still-active naval base is known for the 1941 attack by Japan that brought the U.S. into WWII.

text:
A must visit site in Hawaii. Built to honor not just the lives and memories of the USS Arizona but all service members killed during the attack on Pearl Harbor.

Ensure you come early when visiting. Hundreds of visitors come daily for the chance to step aboard the Arizona Memorial. Visitors line up to reserve time grouped tickets, which are free to the public on a first come basis.

Even if you don't step aboard the Arizona Memorial there are many other sites to see such as the Valor in the Pacific memorial along with the USS Bowfin museum.

This area of the island can get hot during the day especially with the amount of visitors around so drink plenty of water prior to going and throughout the day, and also wear sunblock to avoid getting sunburned.

text:
I wish there was a half star.  Cafe Pesto is a solid 3.5 stars. It's ok and never my choice but I don't argue if folks want to go there.  I can always find something to order.  The price is okay.  It's just... bland and safe.  That's not a bad thing, there needs to be a nicer place for folks who don't want too much adventure in their food, for people who want expected flavor profiles.  Personally, I just like a bit more to my food.  It's why I don choose to eat here.  But it's fine.  When your grandparents from Tulsa visit, it's a great place.  First date? This might be a good testing ground.
Staff is super friendly and it's a clean restaurant.

text: Cafe Pesto is among Hilo's finest restaurants. Nothing is finer than an evening at their establishment. They also, though, have carry out. Their pizzas are second to none. I've ordered up to five pizzas at a time for events at my house. Their service is fast, efficient, and I have gotten only compliments from my guests. Forget about the others. If you're looking for great carryout pizza, call Cafe Pesto.

business_description: Mainstay eatery in a quaint, restored historic space is known for its pizzas from a wood-fired oven.

text:
Big deal people... None of their pesto contains any nuts!!!

I'll let that sink in.

Most pesto is made with pine nuts and some are made with almonds but not at this restaurant for any of you with nut allergies this is the place if you miss eating anything with pesto.

We grabbed the southwest chicken pizza as well as the mango chicken with mashed potatoes both were excellent choices. I would recommend this restaurant to anybody.

Great pizza options, pasta options, and other dishes as well. Lots of local catch choices which change all the time.

text: Very interesting self tour of this great battleship. So much to see below deck and also in the bridge. The kids loved it too. Many guides on the ship provide useful insight. Good for a rainy day in the island.
business_description: Historic battleship, which was the site of the official Japanese surrender in WWII, offers tours.

text: Amazing testament to this time in history and the men who served. I am not normally interested in military history but I really enjoyed the tour. We chose to go at our own pace. I had a few hours but could have spent a full day here.
business_description: Historic battleship, which was the site of the official Japanese surrender in WWII, offers tours.

text: So much history to be proud of. Definitely need a whole day on this ship to appreciate everything.

text: Remarkable experience. They really let you get down in the inside of the ship. There are docents everywhere to explain things. He gave us a really good sense of what living and working on a battleship would be like.

text: This experience should undoubtedly be on your list of stops during your time in Honolulu! text: I thought that I'd enjoy the Air museum the best on this tour but the Missouri was so impressive.  Since the Arizona memorial was closed it was the closest we came, but it felt very "right" to have the start of the US' involvement in the war, and it's conclusion in one place.  The Arizona is well protected by this sleeping giant.  The plaque marking the spot of the surrender and the documents (repros I think) were very moving.  So many people gave their lives.  There is a flag up on the exterior bulkhead by the surrender site, with 31 stars that MacArthur brought to the surrender - it was Commodore Perry's flag that he carried to Japan when he opened trade between our countries in the mid 1800s.  MacArthur had a flair for staging an event!  Tiny details thought through.  You can do a tour or go self-guided as your ticket gets you an audio tour device.  I thought we would be there for a short time but ended up staying over 2 hours.  You get a feel for why they were called our greatest generation.

text: A fascinating journey in time, the "Mighty Mo," stands strong on the site of one of America's darkest hours.She represents the end of the conflict.  Visitors stand on the deck at the precise spot where Japanese representatives surrendered as the Missouri rested in Tokyo Bay in September 1945.  The ship has become a floating museum.  Especially moving are the exhibits dealing with the sea battle of Okinawa and the fight with Kamikaze attacks.  Letters from the Japanese pilot who died while crashing his plane aboard this ship may be seen, as well as the dent in the battleship's gunwales where his plane struck the ship's bulwarks.

text: What a historic battleship. World war 2 effectively ended in this ship. This is also the ship that fired the first Tomahawk missiles. There is a lot to see on this ship. There is also so much to learn. This ship took a direct hot from a kamakazi pilot. The exact location where it happened is marked and there is a picture as well of the moment before impact where you can clearly see the aircraft next to the ship before impact. There is so much to learn at this place. My wife and I thoroughly enjoyed our time here.

text:
I'M GOING TO START OFF BY SAYING THAT IF YOU COME TO HAWAII AND DO NOT TAKE AT LEAST ONE DAY TO VISIT PEARL HARBOR YOU SHOULD BE DAMN ASHAMED OF YOURSELF!! THIS IS A SACRED PLACE TO A TRUE AMERICAN.

COMING ABOARD THE USS MISSOURI WAS ABSOLUTELY AMAZING. THE SIZE, THE MIGHT, THE HISTORY...IT WAS ALOT TO TAKE IN. SEEING THE PHOTOGRAPHS OF EVENTS THAT TOOK PLACE EXACTLY WHERE I STOOD ON CERTAIN PARTS OF THE SHIP ALMST MADE ME FEEL LIKE I WAS THERE.

YOU CAN EITHER TOUR WITH A GUIDE OR CHECK OUT AN AUDIO DEVICE THAT TELLS YOU THE SAME INFO AS THE GUIDE. THERE IS NO EXTRA COST. DRIVERS LICENSE IS COLLATERAL. IF YOU DO DECIDE TO GO WITH THE ELECTRONIC DEVICE BE SURE TO LOOK ALL AROUND FOR THE NUMBERS PAINTED ANYWHERE AND EVERYWHERE TO PUNCH IN.

text: A lot of WWII history here. If you are willing to spend the money, and have the time, then I recommend this place highly. Your tour guide will probably be a volunteer dedicated to preservation of the memorial. Ours had a lot of insight and little known facts. There are plenty of photo ops. It takes a while to walk the whole ship. You are allowed to go off on your own below deck. Bring your own water if able. The price is considerable vs. Pearl Harbor. You have to take a shuttle from the Pearl Harbor memorial. There is parking at PH, but be aware of thieves and other scum that are looking for an easy score. Egress is a bit confusing so use a GPS to get out OK.

text:
After we finished the Aviation Museum we got picked up and we were taken to the USS Missouri. Once our group was semi sort of together we we given to an English speaking tour guide Val, she was great by the way.
She walked us through the main deck of the "Mighty Mo" given us a lot of information of the Battleship, and it is best remembered as the site of the surrender of the Empire of Japan which ended WWII on Sept 2nd 1945 in Tokyo Bay.
While we walked along the way you can see a dent just below the main deck level of the Missouri. It turns out a low flying Kamikaze hit it and only made very minimal damage. The remains of the pilot were recovered on board, the crew wanted to get rid over the side. But Captain Callaghan decided the young pilot had done his job to the best of his abilities, and with honor, so he should be given a military funeral. The next day he was buried at sea. Val informed us since they had no Japanese flags around, the crewmembers managed to find a way to make one before burying him at sea. You see the footprints made of where it was done.
After she concluded her part of the tour we were left to tour by ourselves, we were just told one thing " don't take pictures of (I can't remember which side of the ship lol) because that's still an active military base" So we climbed our short butts to the top deck to take some pictures lol of the side that we could.
This is definitely worth a stop if you're in the area.

text:
This is a very interesting memorial and fascinating to tour the ship which has been kept in such excellent condition - partly because of course it was renovated for active service in the 1980s, and also through the efforts of the preservation team.

The Heart of the Missouri tour was well worth the extra for a guided tour into the more private areas lower down the ship, with a knowledgeable guide.

The only issue which prevents me giving it 5 stars is that the website is really not very good.  Obviously written by people who understand the system, we found it difficult to bolt on the Heart Of Missouri tour to the main tickets - quite time consuming and frustrating.

Also when waiting to board the ship, we were made to wait in a queue to be processed through a photographic stage, despite saying we did not want our photographs taking.  So we waited 10 minutes to be allowed to get to the front of the queue just to decline the pics and board - it's just unnecessary and irritating

text:
When I was younger I saw one of the photographs showing the representatives of Japan standing aboard USS Missouri to sign the surrender and ending the WW2. So it was a great experience to be standing on the same deck where the historic fact happened. And it is also relevant that you are at Pearl Harbor, where the war started for the United States, and at the same time you are on the vessel where the end of the war was signed.
The visit to the Missouri has a guided tour, that is very good and informative. I really recommend.

text: The USS Missouri Memorial is awesome! Stand in the footprints where the treaty was signed ending World War II. See were a Japanese Kamikaze pilot struck the ship. USS Missouri stands watch over the USS Arizona, and it's absolutely amazing to stand on the teak decks of this glorious battleship! Many promotion and retirement ceremonies are held on the fantail of the ship. The guides are very knowledgeable and often have some personal connection to the USS Missouri, making the events they speak about all the more compelling. If you're on Oahu stop by the USS Missouri! You'll be glad you did!

text:
If you visit Pearl Harbor, this is one of the memorials you have to visit. "The Mighty MO" along with the "USS Arizona Memorial" is a must see. We toured this awesome ship right after our tour of the USS Arizona Memorial and USS Bowfin Submarine. We arrived early and was lucky to get tickets for the USS Arizona Memorial, but I was smarter and purchased our tickets well in advance for this tour.

To get the opportunity and privilege to tour this living museum was an honor and one that our family with not forget. To this day, the Missouri continues to serve the public by telling its story for visitors from around the world and it's anchored in a fitting place here at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.

text: The Battleship Missouri is a historical Naval vessel that has defended the US for many years. She has been turned into a museum so the people can understand the trials and tribulations of what the sailors of the past had to go through. The year 2019 marked the 75th Anniversary to her commissioning. This place is family friendly, people who have trouble getting around such as going up and down stairs and or ladders may have trouble visiting this place.

text: During our 5-night stay at Four Seasons Resort Oahu at Ko Olina in late June, 2018, we visited this Battleship Missouri Memorial after visiting USS Arizona Memorial. Frequent shuttle buses connected Battleship Missouri Memorial and WWII Memorial Park where USS Arizona Memorial was located. As we approached Battleship Missouri, we became awe struck by the majestic battleship ahead of us. Passing by the life size cutout of a U.S. sailor kissing a stranger nurse at NY Times Square in an exhilarating celebration of the WW II V-J Day, we climbed up to the deck to explore the ship. The ships' mighty guns, situation room, computer room, the rooms with pictures of the ship's past engagements in multiple wars, crews quarters, engine rooms, messhall, and armored decks were all very impressive. Above all, the historical spot on the main deck, where Japanese delegations and Allied Nations' delegation led by General McArthur signed the documents ending WWII with Japan's surrendar, was most impressive and memorable. This battleship memorial is a must-see memorial for the visitors to Oahu, Hawaii.

text: This one is a little drive on a shuttle bus to Ford Island. The ship itself is massive. You can also have an audio tour with this one, but they weren't clearly marked on where to pick it up. It's near the beginning somewhere...we got all the way on to the ship and they said "Oh you have to pick them up down there." We decided against waiting in line again so we just went around on our own. They were doing the deck restoration or the teak wood deck when we were there. It was really amazing to think of how long this ship had been in commission, and to see the difference in the restored deck to the old deck. I often feel great pride in my country whenever we do a tour at Pearl Harbor. It is amazing the things we have accomplished.

text: A rare opportunity to glimpse a key piece of naval hardware that played an integral role throughout multiple key points during the 20th Century. The basic tour only covered a limited space on the ship, which at first, I couldn't understand given the sheer size of the vessel. Essentially you tour the bow and starboard sides, a bit of the tower, then are left on your own to explore the rest. Once we started below deck, we understood why - the fact that the ship was retrofitted in the 80's means that you get all of its glory (or lack thereof), which means "old" but not in an interesting historical way. So many of the passageways were deserted and sparsely documented, it just felt a bit creepy being so alone in such a large space. I hope in the future more will be done to restore the interior, so my advice would be to skip below the deck (or just do a brief tour), and move onto other sites in the Monument.

For those of you seeking to swim, there is not much available regarding public access. However, locals know trails. Go talk to a local to get advice but be warned, your taking risks. These falls are definitely easy to visit and provide am extremely short and worthwhile trek up to the top. Parking is free and I don't recall seeing a bathroom, so be aware. You can continue on beyond the water fall if you want to on a short trek to see some unique trees and an awesome canopy. You can also choose to go on the overlook side and stand across from the falls to view them head on.

At the top of the trail there are signs that indicate you cannot go past a certain point, but I believe they're there to keep you off the cliff side. Just be cautious when venturing past the paved area as there are a lot of roots on the ground and can be slippery when it's raining - as it was when we visited.

Unfortunately, there were no rainbows as it was incredibly overcast and rainy when we were there, but it was still worth the trip.

text: Very beautiful and easy to find. The trail goes up beyond the viewing area a little way and there is a huge banyan tree to explore. There were lots of kids climbing in the tree and screetching like monkeys, which was fun. There were some teenagers hanging out in the parking lot, which is normal for any park in any city that has teenagers (all of them) but with all the signs warning about theft and loitering I couldnt help but feel paranoid.    I dont know how bad the theft problem is in Hilo or at this park, but they sure like to make you think you cant walk away from your car without the window being smashed out and your car being stripped. Our car was fine, nobody robbed us, and those teenagers were just teenagers finding a place to be teenagers. Dont let the signs startle you too much.

text: Ah where to start. I ordered online for a curbside order. I arrived at the Holly Bush location and clicked "I'm here" on the app. Upon doing so, I was prompted to call the store instead. I did and the phone rang 8 times when it was answered and I was abruptly put on hold. OK, that's fine. Maybe they were busy. I counted 7 workers as I sat there looking in. Multiple employees just standing there. After 3 minutes being on hold, I hung up and called back. This time the phone rang 12 times so I gave up and went in myself. I received my dinner box (2 medium 1 topping, breadsticks and 6 traditional wings) only to find I received cheese sticks instead of garlic sticks and 3 wings instead of 6. Soooo needless to say, I'll drive 10 more minutes to go to Papa John's from now on.

text: Eating at Pizza Hut was a routine part of my life growing up, but the Pizza Hut here in Brandon, Mississippi is filled with the most utterly incompetent, uncaring, and unfriendly employees I have ever had the disservice to meet in any encounter with a business.  I just ordered three orders of cheese sticks from this location with three extra marinara sauce.  When I arrived at the drive thru I received two orders and four cups of marinara sauce.  I explained to the employee at the window that I had ordered three orders and all she wanted to do was point out they charged me for two.  She finally called the manager over, who clearly should not be the manager of anything, and all she did was explain the same thing and tell me I could order another, pay for them, and wait 15 minutes for them to get done, all the while messing with her phone.  Regrettably, I paid for what I got and left.  I wish I had left and not bought anything.  I will never return to this Pizza Hut, which is unfortunate since they have a nice, albeit dirty play area where my kids enjoy spending time.  I simply cannot justify giving my hard earned dollars to a business owner who clearly has no desire to improve the quality of employees so that they can at least do their job.

When we want to unwind and enjoy the sights and scenery near the marsh, this is one of our favorite destinations.

text: I spent a lot of time cycling along the coast, during my vacation to the Gulfport and Biloxi area. It was scenic and I saw a variety of shore birds, pelicans, herons, etc. Some of the piers were blocked off and still damaged from the last hurricane. For the most part, the paved access along the beach was in pretty good shape. There were a couple of sections still damaged by the last hurricane, where you had to carry your bike over. One thing I didn't like was seeing the signs with rules against dogs on the miles of beach and the "NO FIREARMS OF ANY KIND ALLOWED" A person, legally licensed to carry a handgun, should be able to carry and protect themselves and family, while walking or cycling along the beach.

text: Run! This pizza hut does not respect their customers. On more than one occasion, my pizzas were OLD. They cook pizzas way ahead of time then give you the ones that taste like they have been sitting out for hours. If you order another topping, they will just add the other toppings to an old pizza then reheat. I complained about this through email and customer service sent me a code for free pizzas. Honestly, I don't want to waste my time using the free pizza coupon because it is just that nasty. The reason why I am so mad is because I buy additional food whenever I use the coupon. The only time I received good pizza was when I ordered during the daytime on a weekday. Please do better so you wont lose another customer. The Cinnabon dessert taste like plastic with cream on it. The only food item that tastes good is the chocolate chip cookie.

text: Since covid quarantining, my best friend and I had been craving a little normalcy. After getting our vaccines, we planned a date and we picked the Camp. Rendy made delicious drinks--a dirty martini and a HUGE old fashion. Both made impeccably! The bar food--wings, sliders, fries! The burgers one with pepper jack cheese and jalapenos; the other slathered with guacamole! YUM! All the food and drinks were delicious! But the service was FANTASTIC! Rendy was a great bartender and server. She served personality plus! The ambiance inside the bar and the water right outside made this visit a definite return!

text: Revised review..Called to see if the dining room was open with booths available and was told yes. So we arrived at around 5:40 and I ask for a booth and was told that the booths are only for parties of 4 or larger. They have large party booths and smaller ones.   we've  sat at a both with 2 before. Seated at small table.  We had a cute little girl seated next to us,  running the entire time all around the dining room and running circles around us and hiding between my chair and the wall.  She almost ran into a server who had her hands full of plates. I was not happy having to watch  the 2 empty booths our entire meal, as we were paying and leaving they were finally seated with 2 PARTIES OF 2!!!  When I called I wish I had been told only parties of 4 and up were allowed at booths.  I'm disabled and booths are always a better option for me. Service was ok. We ordered what we've had in the past. We come at least once a month. I always get the full size bbq pork sandwich. Last time I ordered it I thought they gave me the smaller one by mistake but I didn't question it as they were very busy. This time it was the same. Its almost half the size it used to be. My daughter made the same comment. Times are tough so im sure they are just cutting costs.   Don't know if I'll be back or not.
business_description: Pub fare from tacos to burgers, plus many craft draft beers, offered in a cozy, old-school setting.

My wife got the fried shrimp platter, both were delicious. If you are in a hurry, this is not the place. We were not in a hurry so, it was a pleasant experience. Waiter was nice and made sure everything was OK multiple times. We will return to try out other items on the menu. If I have one complaint about the food, it would be the nacho appetizer, there was barely any pulled pork on them. It tasted great though, just needed a little more on it. I still recommend trying it out if you have the chance. Slightly on the pricey side but, you won't feel as if you've been cheated.

text: I eat here from time to time. I ordered the thick sliced roast beef, with Lima beans and cinnamon apples as a side....The Lima beans were masterful...Well seasoned...Cooked through without being mushy.... .the cinnamon apples were just right...Not so sweet as to be overbearing, but just enough for a dessert.....The roast beef was good...Tender .. unfortunately a little bit dry....It could have been trimmed a bit leaner...the gravy had a good consistency but was a little bland...A bit of salt resolved it.  The tea was a good effort. Solid flavor and sweet enough...However it was missing that little extra from making it the day before and letting it age overnight in the refrigerator.  All in all worth the visit.

text: Cracker Barrel is a wonderful place to enjoy a quick, delicious meal with loved ones. I finally got something other than my usual breakfast Grandma sampler. I ordered the baked rainbow trout seasoned with lemon pepper. Delicious! I had perfectly steamed broccoli and loaded sweet potato which included huge marshmallows,  pecans, butter and brown sugar. Amazing flavor. My husband enjoyed a generous slice of meatloaf, steamed broccoli,  mashed potatoes,  and turnip greens.  My sister-in-law enjoyed country fried streak covered with white pepper gravy, mashed potatoes and mac and cheese.  My brother-in-law had delicious fried Catfish, turnip greens and mac and cheese. We all enjoyed a slice of delicious buttermilk pie. Our waiter Taye was absolutely wonderful. We always receive great customer service when we visit Cracker Barre especially our favorite one l located in Southaven, MS.

text: This was an interesting experience. It was our first time diving out since the pandemic started. There was a wait which was expected considering the current circumstances. The wait for a table wasn't long once we got on the list. The unorganized, uncomfortable wait in line to get on the list took over 15 minutes. The hostess stand was well inside the gift shop which caused the line to wind through the gift shop and not everyone waiting exercised social distance. Once we were seated, it took no time for our server to approach. She was super friendly and effective. Our food was served hot and prepared just as requested. Then we saw the strangest thing that actually reduced the stars here. We saw another server was tasked with cleaning the menus after the guests before they were returned to the hostess using the same dingy towel over and over again. She had a spray bottle of what might have been disinfectant spray but she never used it and she never cleaned her towel or exchanged it for a new towel. Disgusting! The 3 stars are for our actual server and her friendliness. For me, the experience was ruined by the unsanitary practices and the wait time to get on the list. For me, I won't go back.

text: We got there at 10:10 am for breakfast. The country store was teaming with guests. They took our names for the waitlist and surprisingly the wait was less than 15 minutes. Our server took our drink orders. I asked her to bring iut the biscuits before the meal. Theses were the fluffiest biscuits I've gotten from Cracker Barrel! I ordered a fried pork chop,grits,2 eggs and hashbrown casserole. The pork chop tasted like it was on the verge of of becoming rancid. I replaced with fried catfish. It was perfectly crispy, it just was more batter than fish! After adding a half teaspoon of salt to my grits they were the perfect taste and consistency! My hashbrown casserole was the right texture. It got crowded in the dining area after we were seated. It was hard to hear each other talk. Our server kept our drinks refilled. I would have been satisfied with biscuits and sweet tea. I normally get the country ham, so I won't venture away from the ham again. We are meeting there in two weeks. Biscuits with apple butter,  ham,hashbrown casserole and grits await me.

text:
Awful! I will never go to this location again. It took 45 mins to get our food and even then, some of the sides were missing which meant more wait time. The food was warm but not hot and was sub par at best.

Our waiter was nice enough and attentive enough, but the wait was uncalled for. We arrived at a time that should normally be a dinner rush but they were not busy at all. Now I understand why! I have always loved Cracker Barrel, but this was not a good experience. My daughter is six months pregnant and we had a 3 and 5 year old with us. Kids don't do well waiting that long when they are hungry

To top everything off,  I think we were overcharged. We asked about the price of the kid's meals at the register, and the girl at the register was really rude. Her answer was "I don't know," instead of finding out. The prices weren't on the kid's menus. She also kept talking to someone about gum over her headset instead of taking care of us.

My 5 year old grandson chose the place to eat because it was his reward for making a 100 on his math test. It was a 30 min drive to get there and a total waste of time and money. We were all very disappointed.

text: I called in and placed an order for pick up. I got there at the time they said it would be ready and the cashier said it was not ready yey. I asked if I could add a drink to my order. He said well...ummmm....I guess I could track down the person that took your order and tell her you want to add a drink..... I said nevermind. It sounded like too much trouble. I paid for my order and was told they would call me. I told them again that I was hearing impairedso please make sure I heard. 45 min after my order was supposed to be ready, I asked about it and the girl said "It's been ready. We called your name." and proceeded to pick up one of the bags that had been sitting there since I walked in. I said something about it being cold and she shrugged and said "We called you.". When I got home, items were missing that I ordered and was charged for, and there were things on my receipt that I didn't order, not to mention the food was awful. I called the manager and he said he had refunded the amount of the entire check back to my card. It is still on there with no refund. I would not recommend this place to anyone.

text: Absolutely INCREDIBLE food! Arguably THE BEST in Memphis. Side note (for this location in particular) you do NOT come here expecting phenomenal service. text:
Mr. Neely, I called your establishment close to 8pm tonight and tried to make a to go order after the young man explained to me what was included in a 12 pack pulled pork combo. He told me that your establishment doesn't take to go orders an hour before closing. He said I would either have to come through the drive thru or come in to place my order. My husband and I left our home and arrived at your establishment at 8:30pm. We drove thru the drive thru first, but no one would assist us. We then parked and my husband attempted to go inside to order. The door was locked. There were at least three young men and a young lady inside who saw him at the door. Instead of assisting him, they started laughing and giving each other high fives! This is not the type of service we expected from your business. We left your establishment and went to your competitor Tops Barbeque and the drive thru was busy and so was the inside. My husband went inside, placed our order and had our food in a matter of minutes. The service was great!  We've always loved your barbeque but with service like we received tonight, We Won't Be Back!! We thought you deserved to know how your employees are running your business!

Marcia and Curtis Cobb
January 30, 2020

text:
Perhaps this restaurant one had awesome barbeque, as in, 1989, when this place was actually winning awards for the food they prepared. In modern times however, as in, 2016, this place has the worst barbeque I have tried to date. How much barbeque have I tried you ask: well, I eat barbeque at least once a week in the Memphis area, and have done so for a few year now.
The sauce here is awful. Looks like thick ketchup mixed with grease, then poured all over the rib plate. Ribs were overcooked to the point of the meat just falling apart. Seasoning was almost nonexistent, and there was zero smoke flavor or smoke ring. I would not recommend this place to anyone for any reason.

text:
Ghengis grill in California is just cheap mall food. Here they try and charge you way more than what it's worth and make it into a restaurant. It ain't that serious! They have different size bowls, but it's small for what they're charging you. A lot to choose from, but I don't like the fact that the raw meat isn't quick freezed, but left out to thaw.

They cook everything on one grill, so good luck to the vegetarians, they cook meat on it too. I've always found little char burnt niblets in my food. text: We recently went here to get breakfast. We arrived at 9:20 and were seated very quickly. The restaurant was nearly empty. The waiter was very friendly and did a great job. After waiting around 40 minutes we started to get a little irritated that the food wasn't there. We asked the waiter and he said it would be soon. At 10:20, a full hour later, the waiter came back and said that they were missing half of our order and that they would start on it now. I asked to speak to the manager at this point. She came out and was very rude and aggressive. Before I got to even say anything she went off on me about how they had to make the pancake batter and it takes a while to make it and did not offer a single apology. We told her we wanted to cancel it and she said, "okay, fine". As we got up to leave our waiter started to walk out with our food and she yelled at him and said, "take it back! They said they don't want it anymore!". This was the worst restaurant experience I have ever had. I've never seen a manager behave so childish and unprofessional. My wife and I love eating at Denny's but this is the last time we ever go there.
business_description: Casual diner chain dishing up classic American comfort fare, including breakfast, 24 hours a day.

text: We were here two days in a row, over a weekend.  Food was good, pancakes were fluffy and tasty. My food had cooled off before coming to the table, while wifey's food was hot on arrival. text: I have been here twice and had a bad experience both times.  In both instances, the apple slices given to my children were expired.  On my first trip, they replaced them apologetically.  On my second trip, they gave me another bag that wasn't expired, but upon opening the bag, you could smell they were rancid.  When I brought them back up, I was told, "Well, they aren't past their expiration date."  When I asked for another option, the cashier wanted to charge me for a completely new item.  I fought for about 5 minutes before they just threw a bag of chips across the counter and said, "Fine, here, just take it."  Another member of our party did not get the ordered mayo on her sandwich, so she asked for a cup of mayo from the kitchen.  The waitress brought back a squeeze packet.  Our guest explained that she prefers the regular mayo instead of the squeeze packet, and kindly asked if she could just get it from a cup from the kitchen.  5 minutes later nothing had happened yet.  She went to the counter where a manager told her that she could not have mayo from the kitchen because they were busy and had a long line (which they did).  My family member expressed that this would not have been a problem if it were fixed according to her order.  The manager stomped back to the kitchen and grabbed the mayo for her, handing it to her with anger.  We will not return to this restaurant again for sure!
business_description: This casual regional chain serves updated takes on classic deli fare with a Southern twist.

text: I'm not sure if anyone has brought this up but please do something about the dumpster water pond. It's flowing down an incline from the dumpster and stagnating around the menu, probably soaking into the landscaping. text:
This location was not ready to open. The team members are still in training and they are battling hour long waits still. Every time I've been to this location so far, which is like once a day since opening, it's gotten worse. They needed more time to train staff. You can see the older workers training while they are trying to service the influx of customers. My orders are usually wrong every time. The team is nice and all but management clearly didn't given them enough time.

I was kinda annoyed that I sat in a chair to wait on my to go order inside the location, which was taking about 30 minutes even though inside wasn't packed at all. I was told I couldn't sit in the chair because of COVID so I stood in front of the chair. Not sure how that stopped COVID though. It's not like I was dining in, which I understand but 30 minutes standing up waiting for a drink is a bit much of an expectation. They just weren't prepared to open and should have waited or provided more time for training.

text: We stopped here during a road trip in the middle of the week about mid afternoon. The location was clean. Access in and out of the roadways wasn't difficult. The drive thru had adequate space for a larger truck to go through easily. There was only one car in line in front of us. There were about 4 cars in the parking lot. The person taking our order at the drive thru did have some difficulty with customized orders. For instance: No Whip (no whipped cream). The wait was terribly long to get to the window. The person ahead of us ordered only one beverage. As we looked inside there appeared to be only one customer in the store. The person working the drive thru seemed to be frazzled. Our orders were incorrect but we kept them anyway. The wait was too long to ask for what we ordered. We were on a road trip so we didn't have time to be picky. We didn't notice initially but the cups were very sticky. I think some Syrup was spilled and we didn't get a fresh cup or have the cup wiped clean. We didn't receive any napkins either. Maybe the staff was having a bad day. Maybe I expect better because my local Starbucks does such a phenomenal job on all these things. Overall, the beverages were still acceptable and enjoyed. The location was clean. There was an unusual wait time for the number of customers for the store at that time. I would visit this Starbucks again, but probably wouldn't if I was in a rush or had time to make it to a different location in Hattiesburg.

text: They're hot, then they're cold. It's yes then it's no. I'm in then I'm out lol we love pizza. But this location is so inconsistent. The past year has been good. The quality of the food currently is amazing and the delivery drivers are more pleasant. My most recent pizza was not a great one but the manager on duty was. I can definitely give get another shot.And  still, convenience beats cooking a full course meal for 5 after a long day at work any day of the week. Garlic parmesan wings are my absolute favorite. The Oreo cookie and the brownie so good that I warm them and add ice cream on top. This location does not put the right amount off cheese on the pizzas so if you love cheese like i do, double it up.
business_description: Family-friendly chain known for its made-to-order pizzas.

text:
Lets start with the food.  It's on par with what you expect from a Pizza Hut.  This is a massive chain, so you know what the consistency of their pizza is.

This location frustrated me with the service however.  My order was supposed to be ready for pickup at a time well before the lunch crowd.  I showed a few minutes early with the expectation to wait.  15 minutes later my pizza was done (it only takes 20 minutes to cook, so they were obviously late getting it in the oven).  The dessert however took another 30 minutes of standing around waiting before it was done.  At 10 minutes before I got the food, I was told it would be done in 5.

The two people working this location either need some help, time management assistance, or motivation.  The fact that I waited that long for my food while I heard the manager tell people theirs would be done in 20 minutes is frustrating too.

Beyond the timeliness, there was a severe lack of concern when the staffing spoke to me.  The timing is what frustrated me, but this apathy is why I am posting a review.

C'mon guys.  Customer service is everything.
business_description: Family-friendly chain known for its made-to-order pizzas.

text:
Stick to the pizza! We've enjoyed the pizza quite a few times so far, but decided to branch out today. Ordered a sub with no red onions - it ended up being piled high with them. I tried to get them all out, but missed quite a few that were hiding between the meat layers or melted into the cheese. Looks like I'll be popping the Rolaids tonight! The sub was promising otherwise - toasted like a grinder. We also tried the Cinna Squares. Not bad, but they forgot the frosting! I didn't notice until after I got back home and emptied the bag. I've gotten used to having to check my takeout orders at fast food places, but didn't think I'd have to here. Fortunately, the pizza was as good as usual.

I haven't minded paying a little more for a good pizza, but I almost always get something else (wings, sides, etc.) with the order. So even if the pizza's great, the team needs to be on target with the rest of the order. Otherwise, I may have to go back to the old rotation.

text:
I attempted to call in the order but I was placed on hold. Remaining in hold I drove to the restaurant. I walked in with my phone on speakerphone still in hold. I stood at the counter watching the workers walk past me going take sick as sweeping. Several people saw me but never acknowledge me. Finally over employee came to the counter and answered a phone call. He took their order and then asked if he could help me. I shower him my phone letting him hear the hold music and see the time and explained that I've been on hold for over 30 minutes. He said "ooooh" and disconnected their phone from the line. Didn't apologize or inform any other employees, nothing. Acted as if it was no big deal.
He took my order and walked off. As I was waiting the 15 minutes for my order to be prepared I watched employees walk around aimlessly and the manager sit in a booth on her cell phone gossiping. One employee walked out from the back and asked had anyone helped me. The manager said to him"no we're just all sitting here looking at her". I know it was a joke but I found it in terrible taste considering the circumstances.

text: We went to Phoenicia for lunch on a weekday. The main dining room was pretty full but we never felt crowded. Overall a great atmosphere with great inexpensive menu choices available.

text:

text:
There's eating out and then there's the fine art of dining. The Phoenicia Gourmet Restaurant combines every element for an outstanding dining experience.
As soon as I walked through the door, one of the staff was there to greet me. I was led into a bright, airy room with linen tablecloths and napkins. There was a young man playing the violin (my favorite part of the overall experience).
I was there for brunch with friends and we all enjoyed ourselves. The food on the buffet was extremely diverse and the cost included endless Mimosas. It was delicious!
The ambience of this restaurant is head and shoulders above any restaurant I've been to in awhile. The wait staff was excellent, absolutely first rate! I highly recommend Phoenicia Gourmet Restaurant!

The female who answered the phone replied with a long sighful "Okaaaayyyyyy...." and said nothing else. So I said "okay thank you so much!" and ended the call.

My pizza was cold and had barely any cheese and there were places where the cheese looked like it had been scraped away and all that was left was sauce. Garlic stuffed bread was stale and mostly hollow. Wings were good but the rest was Nasty.  Pizza hut is literally 5 min away from my home. Unacceptable. I emailed corporate and they made it right with coupons but this locations service is terrible. The delivery driver, a young black male, seemed nice. I feel bad for him working such a terrible place.

text:
Service for pick-up is always friendly, helpful, exactly what I ordered, and exactly on time. I've never had a bad experience picking up an order after years of being an 'every-other-week' customer.

Standing at the counter and watching activity on the floor, it's obvious that they're understaffed or whoever is doing the scheduling needs to pay better attention to peak times. The server was running her butt off and doing her best in an impossible situation. (This isn't a one time thing either. I see it many times when I'm there for a pick-up.)

Remember that dine-in customers pay for cleanliness and service more than they pay for the food. If you're hungry, even sub-par food tastes great, but they'll always remember bad dine-in service.

Eat the cost of a month of higher than normal payroll for a month or so, provide better service and you'll see that your customer base will increase. It's a 'spend money to make money' thing.
business_description: Family-friendly chain known for its made-to-order pizzas.

text: A very well documented museum. I appreciated the local Hattiesburg stories highlighted throughout the exhibits. We learned a lot. As we entered the museum (unscheduled visit) the  manager met us and gave a thorough introduction.
business_description: Museum in a former USO club focused on the history of African American military contributions.

text: Walking through the doors, I was enveloped by history. The USO building was originally used in World War II for African American military men and women. There were replicas of the original furniture placed around the lobby and 40s music piped in. I felt like had stepped back in time. Each exhibit had several short videos to watch about historic figures, were filled with artifacts and haf some pretty cool displays. Check it out!
business_description: Museum in a former USO club focused on the history of African American military contributions.

text: Outstanding historical memorabilias. Museum displays are superbly presented  with the added touch in some instances of virtual presentations. All military branches are represented with highlights of members from the local and surrounding areas. Rich source for significant historical information. Buffalo Soldiers display is awesome. Should be on the must see places to visit.

text: Twon and his partner in crime are inconsiderate. I worked at Pizza Hut in Madison for approximately a month 2 years ago and I was reprimanded and laid off for eating a slice of pizza. The pizza was an incorrect order and the crime syndicate layed me off because the pizza was "reserved" for hungry people in Jackson. Treat your employees better next in the future. I am 28 years old, a veteran, minimum wage earner, father of 2 sons, and student at Mississippi College. No one should be layed off because they ate a slice of pizza. I am human, I get hungry during a shift at work.

text:
So, the kid decided on pizza for supper. I decided it should be Pizza Hut this time.
Placed my order via the app. Short time later, my pizza arrives. I also had ordered a 2 liter Dr Pepper.
The delivery girl said they were actually out of Dr Pepper. She said she thought about calling to see if I wanted to substitute something else, but decided against it. She took it upon herself to stop at Kroger on the way to my house and pick one up.

Two things should be noted here:
She gets that Dr Pepper is life, and
You don't get that kind of customer service anymore these days. I didn't get her name, but she is awesome, and is my hero for the day.
business_description: Family-friendly chain known for its made-to-order pizzas.
